The legality of cousin marriage and its acceptance varies across different cultures and jurisdictions.
In some cultures and countries, cousin marriage is legal and socially acceptable, while in others it is prohibited or discouraged.
From a genetic perspective, cousin marriages can increase the likelihood of certain genetic disorders in the offspring.

This is because cousins share a higher percentage of their DNA than unrelated individuals, and if both carry the same harmful gene, there is an increased chance that their offspring will inherit two copies of that gene, leading to a genetic disorder.
However, the risk of having a child with a genetic disorder as a result of cousin marriage is generally low.

In many countries, cousin marriage is legal and socially accepted, but it is still recommended that individuals who are considering cousin marriage seek genetic counseling to assess their individual risks and to make an informed decision.
Ultimately, whether or not to marry a cousin is a personal and cultural decision that should be made based on individual circumstances, values, and beliefs.
Bantu has grown up suffering his father Valmiki’s vitriolic tongue until he discovers that he’s actually an heir to an influential family, who was exchanged at birth
He moves into their mansion to protect them from a criminal drug lord’s attack and helps the family sort their issues

The film, which is a remake of a Telugu film Ala Vaikunthapurramuloo, starts on a promising note, as a nurse and an office clerk, Valmiki (Paresh Rawal), exchange the latter’s son with a business magnate Randeep Jindal’s (Ronit Bose Roy)
For 25 years, Valmiki’s son Bantu is trapped in a middle-class household with his spiteful father
The film follows the young guy as he discovers who he really is and vows to protect his real family from a villainous drug mafioso, Sarang (Sunny Hinduja)
Kartik is effortless as the incorrigible, brave and good-hearted Bantu and does well in the action sequences, but there’s nothing fresh about his performance here
The fight choreography deserves a special mention, with its slow-motion and macro videography, and also Sudeep Chatterjee’s cinematography is also good
While the title track sung by Sonu Nigam, ‘Shehzada’, stands out, the others are just average
Shehzada is meant to be enjoyed for its campy humour, irreverent hero, and action sequences
If watching a mass entertainer with a gang of friends is your jam, you could make a trip to the theatre for this one

Education is an essential part of every person's life.
It provides individuals with the knowledge and skills needed to succeed in their careers and personal lives.
However, not all students learn in the same way.
Traditional teaching methods often follow a one-size-fits-all approach, which can leave some students feeling left behind.
That's where personalized learning comes in.
Personalized learning is an educational approach that tailors the learning experience to meet the unique needs of each student.
It takes into account each student's learning style, interests, and abilities, and adapts the curriculum accordingly.
With personalized learning, students have more control over their education, which can lead to greater engagement and improved outcomes.
One of the main benefits of personalized learning is that it can help bridge the achievement gap.
Students who come from disadvantaged backgrounds or who have learning difficulties may struggle in a traditional classroom setting.
Personalized learning can help these students catch up to their peers and even surpass them.
For example, a student who struggles with reading may benefit from a program that uses visual aids or audiobooks to help them learn.
Another advantage of personalized learning is that it can help students build skills that are relevant to their future careers.
In traditional classrooms, students are often taught a standard curriculum that may not be directly applicable to their future jobs.
Personalized learning can help students develop specific skills and knowledge that will be useful in their chosen field.
For example, a student interested in graphic design may benefit from a program that focuses on design software and digital art techniques.
Personalized learning can also help students develop a love of learning.
Traditional teaching methods can sometimes be boring or unengaging for students, leading to disinterest and even dropping out.
With personalized learning, students have more control over their education, which can lead to greater motivation and curiosity.
For example, a student who is interested in science may benefit from a program that allows them to conduct experiments and explore topics in more depth.
Of course, personalized learning is not without its challenges.
One of the main issues is the lack of resources and support for teachers who want to implement this approach.
It can be difficult for educators to design and implement personalized learning programs, particularly in schools with limited funding or large class sizes.
Additionally, there is a lack of research on the long-term effects of personalized learning, which can make it difficult to assess its effectiveness.
In conclusion, personalized learning is an important approach to education that can help students achieve their full potential.

By tailoring the learning experience to meet the unique needs of each student, personalized learning can bridge the achievement gap, develop skills that are relevant to future careers, and foster a love of learning.
While there are challenges to implementing this approach, it is worth the effort to ensure that all students have access to high-quality education.
